data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code has three patterns that break on .NET 8:

| Pattern found | Problem on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires — no abort exists to trigger it |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive, there's no Thread.Abort equivalent.
        // The thread is a background thread, so it will die on process exit.
        // For stronger guarantees, see "Uncooperative code" note below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key changes explained

**1. `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`**
Cancellation is now *cooperative*. The token must be checked or passed to blocking APIs.

**2. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException)`**
The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated ones. Your rollback logic is preserved here.

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed**
No equivalent needed. With cooperative cancellation you control flow explicitly — just `break` out of the loop after cleanup.

**4. `_running` volatile bool → `CancellationToken`**
The token replaces the hand-rolled flag and also integrates with blocking APIs.

**5. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `_workerThread.Join(2s)`**
`Join` actually waits for the thread to finish rather than blindly sleeping.

## Critical: Make `GetNextItem` cancellation-aware

This is the **#1 pitfall**. If `GetNextItem()` blocks (your comment says it may), cancellation will stall there until it unblocks on its own. You must pass the token through:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, ignores cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection
}

// AFTER — wakes up immediately on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` does network I/O or `WaitHandle.WaitOne()`:
```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep with cancellation-aware wait
Thread.Sleep(5000);                    // ❌ ignores cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);        // ✅ wakes on cancel

// Replace WaitHandle.WaitOne with cancellation-aware version
event.WaitOne();                                            // ❌
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle });      // ✅
```

## Common pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing token through the full call chain** | If `ProcessItem` calls 5 methods deep and none check the token, cancellation won't take effect until control returns to the loop |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` — leaks timers and callbacks. The `Dispose()` method above handles this |
| **Expecting cancellation to be instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations inside `ProcessItem` |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Without the `when` guard you'd swallow cancellations from unrelated subsystems |
| **Uncooperative blocking code** | If you call third-party code that blocks without accepting a token, there is **no .NET 8 equivalent** to force-kill that thread. Move such work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` |

The key mindset shift: .NET Framework let you yank the rug out from under a thread. .NET 8 requires the thread to *volunteer* to stop. Every blocking call site must be updated to accept and respect the `CancellationToken`.
